arforth, North Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Barforth Hall, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1250–after 1278":"1250–after 1278","1250–1278":"1250–1278","1250–Female":"1250–Deceased","1278–1342":"1278–1342","1200–1268":"1200–1268","1205–Female":"1205–Deceased","1205":"1205","1259":"1259","1268":"1268","before 1278":"before 1278","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","1342":"1342","1250":"1250","after 1278":"after 1278","England":"England","Barforth, North Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Barforth Hall, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pudsay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Pudsey (WR Yorks), which is recorded as  <i>Podechesai(e)</i> in 1086,  <i>Pudekesseya</i> in the 12th century, and  <i>Pudekeshay</i> in 1219. The place-name probably derives from an Old English personal name * <i>Pudoc</i> (genitive * <i>Pudoces</i>) + Old English  <i>ēg</i> ‘island’. Pudsey stands on the top of a hill, and so in this case  <i>ēg</i> may have the sense ‘hill spur, island of good land in moorland’. Alternatively, the final element may be Old English  <i>(ge)hæg</i> ‘enclosure’ or  <i>hēah</i> ‘high ground, height’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"y